entry.et: Middle English, from Old English nā, from ne not + ā always; akin to Old Norse & Old High German ne not, Latin ne-, Greek nē- aye

dt.un: used as a function word to express the negative of an alternative choice or possibility shall we go out to dinner or no

def.dt: :in no respect or degree used in comparisons you're no better than the rest of us
:not so used to express negation, dissent, denial, or refusal no, I'm not going

dt.un: used with a following adjective to imply a meaning expressed by the opposite positive statement in no uncertain terms
used as a function word to emphasize a following negative or to introduce a more emphatic, explicit, or comprehensive statement it's big, no, it's gigantic
used as an interjection to express surprise, doubt, or incredulity
used in combination with a verb to form a compound adjective no-bake pie

def.dt: :not any no parking no disputing the decision
:hardly any :very little finished in no time
:not a :quite other than a he's no expert

dt.un: used in combination with a noun to form a compound adjective a no-nonsense realist

def.dt: :an act or instance of refusing or denying by the use of the word no :denial received a firm no in reply
